{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528648"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14321"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.47,0.2,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7016"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57964"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7016"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3060"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4019"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57964"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about her alprazolam use. She has been taking 1 mg three times daily for the past two years to manage anxiety. She reports experiencing rebound anxiety between doses and difficulty sleeping if she misses a dose. She has no other significant medical history and takes no other regular medications. On examination, she appears anxious but is otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gradual wean of alprazolam dose","Switch to diazepam and initiate gradual taper","Switch to lorazepam at an equivalent dose and wean","Increase alprazolam dose","Cease alprazolam"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of benzodiazepine dependence, including rebound anxiety between doses and withdrawal symptoms when missing a dose. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eswitch to diazepam and initiate gradual taper\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach is based on the principle of substituting a short-acting benzodiazepine (alprazolam) with a long-acting one (diazepam) to manage dependence and facilitate withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egradual wean of alprazolam dose\u003C/strong\u003E would be less effective than switching to diazepam. Alprazolam is a short-acting benzodiazepine, which can lead to more pronounced withdrawal symptoms between doses, making the tapering process more challenging and uncomfortable for the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to lorazepam at an equivalent dose\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the best choice as lorazepam is also a short-acting benzodiazepine. While it might be slightly longer-acting than alprazolam, it does not offer the same benefits as a long-acting benzodiazepine like diazepam in managing withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the alprazolam dose\u003C/strong\u003E would only exacerbate the problem of dependence and make eventual withdrawal more difficult. It does not address the underlying issue and is not a recommended approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing alprazolam\u003C/strong\u003E abruptly is potentially dangerous and could lead to severe withdrawal symptoms, including seizures. This approach is not recommended due to the risks involved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiazepam is preferred for managing benzodiazepine dependence and withdrawal due to its long half-life and smooth pharmacokinetic profile. This results in a more gradual decline in blood levels, reducing the severity of withdrawal symptoms. The switch to diazepam should be done using equivalent dosing, followed by a gradual taper over several weeks to months, depending on the individual\u0027s response and tolerance. This approach allows for a more controlled and comfortable withdrawal process, minimizing the risk of severe withdrawal symptoms and complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Long-acting benzodiazepines are preferred for managing benzodiazepine dependence and withdrawal due to their smoother pharmacokinetic profile.","Diazepam is often used as the long-acting benzodiazepine of choice in benzodiazepine withdrawal management.","Gradual tapering of benzodiazepines is essential to minimize withdrawal symptoms and reduce the risk of complications."],"references":["Australia H. Prescribing drugs of dependence in general practice, Part B."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T14:59:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T15:28:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7016"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57964"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.